\- Comments to Authors :

The paper addresses an interesting and potentially important problem. It ad=
dresses 2 deficiencies in AgentSpeak(L). First, AgentSpeak(L) often leads t=
o situations where the overall plan to achieve a goal is spread across mult=
iple disparate plans that do not explicitly point to the goals that they ar=
e designed to help achieve. Second, failure handling is difficult in AgentS=
peak(L).<br /><br />The paper is largely understandable (although the Engli=
sh phrasing is awkward in a number of places).<br /><br />Overall, the prop=
osals are novel and well-motivated. On the downside, there are problems tha=
t accrue from changing AgentSpeak(L) in the manner suggested. These problem=
s are not discussed at all, which is probably the biggest negative for this=
 paper.<br /><br />Papers such as this are positioned in a difficult space,=
 where the discourse often boils down to personal preference on a certain p=
rogramming style guides the evaluation of the contribution (rather than som=
e more compelling criterion). <br /><br />Some additional concerns:<br /><b=
r />Where and how is plan failure detected? Some details would help here. T=
he current proposal assumes that an appropriate =E2=80=9Cremove goal=E2=80=
=9D event is somehow generated, but these critical details are missing.<br =
/><br />Should there be any constraints governing the relationship between =
the goal conditions of a plan and the goal conditions of plans that might b=
e invoked in the plan body of the parent plan? At first blush, it would app=
ear that these should be mutually constrained, but the paper seems to avoid=
 the question.<br /><br />A downside to explicitly encoding reactive behavi=
our is precisely that reactive behaviour will need to be explicitly encoded=
. In AgentSpeak(L), the mechanism of subgoals and sub-plans indirectly and =
implicitly achieves the ability to react.<br /><br />The suggestion that Ag=
entSpeak(L) is unable to handle g-plans and e-plans is made at various poin=
ts in the paper. This is contentious. Belief addition and removal events ca=
n also be viewed as the goal addition/removal events =E2=80=93 where the go=
al is to handle the belief added or removed.<br /><br />The first paragraph=
 of Section 4 is confusing. It isn=E2=80=99t clear why the handling of exte=
rnal events requires the invoking of an applicable plan from each intention=
 stack, when normally (in AgentSpeak(L)) one would create a new intention s=
tack for each external event. This is a significant departure, and as point=
ed out earlier, a discussion of the downside to modifying AgentSpeak(L) in =
this fashion should be included.

