\- Comments to Authors :

The authors have proposed an extension to AgentSpeak(L) to enable grouping =
of related strategies and failure handling, though the latter comes &#39;fo=
r free&#39; by enforcing all e-plans to be linked to g-plans. In particular=
, the authors propose a one-to-one correspondence between e-plans and g-pla=
ns, and provide an extension to AgentSpeak to this end, as well as some pre=
liminary experimental results to show that the added overhead is feasible. =
The paper is generally well written and easy to follow.<br /><br />My main =
concern, as discussed below, is that one of the main benefits claimed by th=
e authors, that their proposal improves the overall readability of the agen=
t source code, is not convincing. Moreover, they do not (even analytically)=
 compare the advantages of their syntax/semantics with existing approaches =
such as [25,29], which also seem to offer similar advantages (e.g. declarat=
ive goals), but without the need for explicit programming. <br /><br />Spec=
ific comments follow.<br /><br />The definition of a &#39;goal condition&#3=
9; as a postcondition doesn&#39;t seem quite right, as postconditions are t=
ypically effects brought about by operations/goals (e.g. the add/delete lis=
ts of STRIPS operators). Also the description of the semantics of goal cond=
itions (page 3, second column, first para) is not clear, in particular the =
sentence &#39;However, if a goal condition is defined, having finished the =
body execution is not sufficient to deactivate the goal&#39;. What does &#3=
9;deactivate&#39; mean here, and what happens when a body finishes executio=
n but the goal condition is not met? Is the body immediately restarted? Thi=
s seems to be hinted in the Examples section (&#39;plan execution is going =
to last forever&#39;) but it is not clearly stated anywhere. This semantics=
 seems to be related to declarative goals, e.g. in [29], where a plan/goal =
is retried until its success condition is met. <br /><br />On page 2, left =
column, the +!elab_nums(N) goal has !print_nums(N-1) in its body (in the th=
ird set of plan-rules), which is probably a mistake.<br /><br />The authors=
 seem to say that if elab(N) were an action that takes a long time to compl=
ete, that it could be terminated before it finishes. It is not clear how th=
is can actually happen with actions that represent while loops, for example=
, which must loop many thousands of times before the action (function) can =
complete (return). It is also not clear whether the authors have extended A=
gentSpeak to take into account such &#39;durative&#39; actions, which the a=
uthors also somehow allow to be terminated mid-way through execution. In so=
me other BDI languages such as [29], actions are atomic and cannot be termi=
nated mid-way.<br /><br />In the Example section it is not clear what the v=
ertical bar `|&#39; is meant to be. Is it a logical OR? But since &#39;stop=
&#39; is a proposition, and &#39;.body_done&#39; is an action, this vertica=
l bar syntax is non-intuitive. Having an action to represent the fact that =
a plan-body has completed execution also seems rather &#39;hacky&#39;, comp=
ared to the plan-rules shown on page 2, left column (from standard AgentSpe=
ak). Similarly, the &#39;Single Minded Commitment&#39; for a goal requires =
explicit programming (e.g. the use of &#39;.drop_intention (...)&#39;), whe=
reas it seems to be handled more elegantly in the formalisms of [25,29], vi=
a the declarative goal construct Goal(s,P,f). While the authors do cite the=
se papers there is no comparison w.r.t. what the differences are between th=
e &#39;Single Minded Commitment&#39; approach presented by the authors and =
the approach in [25,29]. For example, Goal(s,P,f) can also drop an intentio=
n P being pursued if &#39;s&#39; or &#39;f&#39; become true. In addition, [=
25] seems to also allow failure handling for e-plans (see rules A^2_goal an=
d A^3_goal).<br /><br />When an e-plan needs to be defined inside multiple =
g-plans, it seems the e-plan needs to be repeated inside all of the g-plans=
, whereas in AgentSpeak(L) the e-plan will only need to be specified once. =
Moreover, it looks like the e-plans that are &#39;related to&#39; g-plans c=
ould be automatically computed based on the effects brought about by standa=
rd AgentSpeak(L) e-plans and the preconditions of g-plans (e.g. &#39;stop&#=
39; affects &#39;not stop&#39; in the left column of page 2), rather than a=
sking the programmer to directly/manually specify (and sometimes repeat) e-=
plans and g-plans in the structure/syntax proposed by the authors. <br /><b=
r />In Section 3.3 the authors have specified a failure goal &#39;-g&#39; *=
inside* the specification of the body of the corresponding g-plan, which is=
 contrary to how it is done in Jason (as mentioned by the authors) and also=
 counter-intuitive. It makes sense to specify, for example, goal +!g1 insid=
e the body of +!g because !g1 actually occurs inside the plan for !g. The f=
ailure handling example on page 2, second column, is also not convincing. F=
irst of all, why would a &#39;println&#39; action ever fail? If it does fai=
l, why would the println(&quot;failure&quot;) action in &#39;-!manage_stop&=
#39; succeed? Also it is not clear how/whether the AgentSpeak semantics can=
 handle such action failure. For example, some other agent programming lang=
uages represent the &#39;failure&#39; of an action as the non-applicability=
 of its precondition, or the failure of a test goal that occurs after the a=
ction (both of which occur within some plan-body).<br /><br />While the eva=
luation seems to suggest that AgentSpeak(ER) is not significantly worse tha=
n ASTRA, a more suitable evaluation would have been to see whether (manual)=
 agent-programming efficiency can actually be improved by the new syntax an=
d grouping of plans proposed by the authors. This would require some sort o=
f carefully designed user study to see whether writing agents in AgentSpeak=
(ER) is faster than writing then in AgentSpeak(L).

